RP reason for having TLC. This isn't to say that good roleplayers can't come up with reasons for it being in place -- it just means that the TLC does not in and of itself facilitate more and/or better roleplaying.<br><br>The main purpose of TLC being implemented server-wide is to cut back on farming. Without getting too much into the specifics, I'll simply say that heavy farming can cause a number of issues and situations to crop up that can degrade the server and that are a hindrance to roleplaying. Having TLC turned on severely limits the ability to farm items.<br><br>However, I would like to question how much of a problem farming would be if the TLC were to be turned off. As others have already pointed out in other threads, FV already has a number of other devices in place to hinder farming and powergaming in general -- the language barrier, the alignment system, the elimination of /ooc and limitations on /shout and /auctions, and especially the one character rule. This last one I believe is particularly important, since removing mules and alts severely limits the amount of loot that a farmer can amass and limits the number of buyers for a potential farmer.<br><br>Furthermore, and this has also all been said already, the TLC has created almost as many problems as it solves. Put quite simply, almost all of the existing quests and zones in the game were not designed with the TLC in mind. For most quests, this is not a problem, but it is not surprising to me at all that there are many quests which are now extremely difficult to complete because of the TLC. <br><br>Some (including Sony) have said that it is perfectly reasonable to need to buy quest items off of other players, creating more interaction and roleplaying opportunities. But the community already seems RP-friendly enough, and the low server population and one character limit has made it harder to find some of these quest items than it should be.<br><br>All of this being said, I'm not quite ready to say that the server would be a better place without TLC. Removing the code would almost certainly result in more farming than at present, especially when you consider the fact that the removal of NO DROP has greatly increased the number of potential items to be farmed.<br><br>As an alternative to a server-wide removal of the TLC, I'd like to offer this solution. I think it solves the problem of broken quests while leaving most of the server free of farmers:<br><br>Break the zones down into three groups. Don't break them up by geographical location or level range -- do it in a fairly random fashion.<br><br>Turn off TLC in one of the three groups, and leave it on in the other two. Every week, rotate which group of zones has TLC turned off.<br><br>The expected results would be as follows: every week, some people would go ahead and farm some items in some of the zones. They would get their items, and make some profit by reselling them to the general populace, which as has already been seen is a much softer market than on regular servers. Meanwhile, two-thirds of the zones would be generally free of any farmers, just as they are now.<br><br>Anyone trying to complete a quest or get an item that is affected by TLC has two options: try to buy what they need from another player like they do now, or wait up to two weeks until the TLC gets turned off in the right zone.<br><br>Best of all, this solution is fairly easy to implement. It does not require someone at Sony to go through each quest to see whether or not it is broken by TLC. Assuming that Sony can turn the TLC on and off with a switch, it should be relatively easy for someone to write a script that does just what I described, and set it up as a cron job that runs automatically each week.<br><br>So what does everyone think? Please post your feedback below -- if there's enough support for this, I'd love to write up a petition and lobby Sony to put this change in.<br><br>Thank you for reading this far.<br><br>Ajaja<br>Humble Dar Khura Recruit of Shar Vahl <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umadrain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>madrain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Kerran Lord</span><br>  Posts: 142<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/8/02 9:16:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1060.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: TLC analysis and my solution</span><hr size=1> I like this idea, to some extent.  Seems very original to me, and is definitely preferable to turning it off completely and would most likely be MUCH faster than reporting to Sony with each messed up quest (I already have the feeling the VI gurus don't give a rip about us as a whole). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/8/02 10:13:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1060.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> TLC analysis and my solution</span><hr size=1> Honestly, I just want to see TLC work as advertised -- only TLC on Lore, Magic, and NoDrop (actually nodrop, not just nodrop on other servers).  It'd be nice for it to only work on Magic, but I could cope with TLC'ing Lore too.<br><br>The rotating idea would work for me too, but I'm afraid that would either a) be too complex for VI to do on a rotating system, or b) make those zones way too crowded during their non-TLC time to make it worth hunting...<br><br>---<br>Kimaya Silverbark<br><br>&quot;I bark at that!